AEHEVNT: Multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular and ductal carcinoma, left breast
AEHCOMM: Participantâ€™s mammogram on 07/12/2017 showed a small 6 MM speculated density in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. She had a left lateral biopsy on her breast on 07/20/2017 and was diagnosed with recurrent invasive carcinoma, ER/PR positive and HER-2 negative by FISH. She was treated surgically with left breast wide local excision on 08/01/2017. Pathology showed multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular (85%) and ductal (15%) carcinoma, Nottingham Grade 3 (score 2 for tubule formation, 3 for nuclear atypia, and 3 for mitosis). DCIS is present. No necrosis of the invasive carcinoma was identified and it measured 2.6 X 2.6 X 3.0 CM. The participant had a left breast re-excision on 08/22/2017 which showed two foci of residual invasive mixed mammary carcinoma (largest focus measuring 12 MM) with 1 MM focal positive margin. Her oncologist prescribed her Anastrozole 1mg QD PO. More oncology records have been requested.

Subject was finishing up a workout when he developed a slight "twinge" in the (L) side of his head. This progressed to include "tingling" sensation to (R) check, lips, (R) arm + hand, especially the (R) pinky and ring fingers. Presented to ER Easton Hospital. CT done immediately and it was clear. MRI clear. Admitted overnight. Symptoms resolved within ~8hrs of initial onset. He reports having a little less mental clarity for a couple days after the event. He gave an example of talking to his sister on the phone, and he did not recall this until his wife told him. The event happened on a Thursday morning and by Sunday morning he was completely back to normal. Since this event he has been commenced on a statin, his Losartan was increased and he was also commenced on Aspirin 81mg QD.

AEOTHERHX: DMS 6/24/19 - Subject with PMH of GERD , HTN, hyperlipodemia presented to local ER with complaints of acute nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain. Pain began 2300 on 4/12/19. Initially attributed to "food poisoning"  but when pain persisted presented to ER. CT abdominal scan showed partial small bowel obstruction.  On exam epigastic and RUQ tenderness present. General surgery was contacted to place a nasogasrtric (NG) tube.  Prior to ER, at home had several episodes of nonbloody no bilious emesis. Had normal bowel movement about one hour after pain began. Was admitted for continued NG tube decompression and IV fluids.  By4/14/19 subject was passing flatus, denied nausea, emesis. NG tube with 1375 ml gastric content. Labs revealed no leukocytosis . H & H stable, electrolytes WNL. No evidence of acute kidney injury. NGT removed and started on clear liquids. Recieved pantoprazole IV for GERD while admitted and had prn zofran IV ordered. By 4/15/19 subject continued to improve. Felt well after breakfast. Labs and vitals were normal subject was discharged home.

AEOTHERHX:
SV 11 Mar 2019. Patient fell down three steps outside while holding hands with her husband on October 4, 2018. The patient currently uses a cane to assist in walking. After she fell, her son David assessed her injuries and determined that they did not need immediate medical attention. After sleeping in, both caregiver, daughter, and participant went straight in to take shower together around 12:30 PM. After several minutes, in hot shower, participant complained of dizziness and fainted. Daughter caught her and lowered her down. Eyes were open, breathing normally, but unresponsive for about two minutes. Afterward, participant got up and was back to her baseline. Resumed usual activities and behavior for remainder of day. And since then, no recurrences. Given that participant was "back to normal" so quickly. Family did not seek medical attention. At the time: no slurred speech, no facial droop, no extremity weakness, numbness, or tingling. No chest pain or palpitations. No dyspnea. No recent illness. No fever or chills. No seizures.

Although her lipase corrected to normal within 3 - 4 days, her pancreatic inflammation did not, and she was unable to tolerate a diet and was sent home on TPN through PICC line. She followed up with the surgeon after discharge from hospital, was started on a liquid diet and slowly advanced to a low fat diet, which she tolerated. TPN was stopped and subject had laparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiogram with surgeon-directed fluoroscopy on 11/19/2019.

Participant was admitted to UK hospital on 26 Jan 2019 from Frankfort Regional Med Ctr for evaluation of leukocytosis. GI bleed with associated coffee ground emesis, leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactic acidosis, myoglobinemia, diarrhea, resulting in patient's death.
AEOTHERHX: Patient began having coffee ground emesis during the evening of 6 June 2020.  Nursing home sent patient to emergency room and she was admitted to the hospital on 7 June 2020.  She was initially noted to be hypotensive with blood pressure of 70/37.  Lab work showed multiple derangements including leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactate 5.4 mmol/L, and myoglobin > 24,000.  She had non-bloody foul-smelling diarrhea.  She was given IV bolus fluids and had improvement in blood pressure.  Diagnosis was GI bleed due to suspected significant intra-abdominal pathology with main concern for ischemic bowel.  Lengthy discussion was had with patient's son/healthcare proxy who is at the bedside.  Due to patient's and sons wishes, decision was made to forego aggressive workup or management.  She was transitioned to comfort care measures including around the clock and as needed analgesia with Dilaudid, Ativan for restlessness, and Haldol for agitation.  Patient expired at 4:40 on 8 jun 2020.  Son called site at 8:38 on 8 Jun 2020 to report.

AE #3 
2/26/2020-2/28/2020 Hospital Admission: coronary vasospasm in setting of recent 5-FU chemotherapy administration.
2/26/2020 Presented to ER with episode of chest pain. Initially in the ER he was pain free.  ECG showed normal sinus rhythm with 1st degree AV block.  Subsequently developed 2nd episode chest pain with diaphoresis and radiation into the left arm.  Tachycardia noted and repeat ECG showed significant ST elevation in the anterolateral leads. He was treated with aspirin, Plavix, heparin, metoprolol, and nitro. The pain resolved.  Angiogram completed 2/27/2020 negative for occlusion requiring intervention. TTE completed. Lower extremity ultrasound to exclude DVT completed as well.  Determined pain was likely secondary to coronary vasospasm in the setting of recent 5-FU administration. He was started on diltiazem 180mg daily and Imdur (Imdur later discontinued) for management. Lisinopril was held.  Consideration of alternative chemotherapy regimens suggested.
take L-arginine 2000 mg 3 times daily - take aspirin 81 mg daily - take atorvastatin 40 mg daily - take sublingual nitroglycerin as needed for chest pain.
Oncology 3/10/2020 Based on the cardiac induced toxicity from the 5 fluorouracil I reviewed the plan to change chemotherapy from FOLFIRINOX to gemcitabine.

Discharge condition stable, pain free, normal blood pressure and heart rate.

Her husband was the person who called EMS because he did not feel he could care for her anymore, and he felt she needed a higher level of care.  Her primary complaint during the ER visit was general abdominal pain, which the care team determined was r/t worsening metastatic colon cancer (see AE #3). Given her presentation at the ED on 02/17/22, the ED providers began palliative care discussions with the family and the participant was place on hospice. Her health quickly declined and she died on 03/14/22 from worsening metastatic cancer (see AE #3). No further details were provided via EMR notes on frequency or onset of her falls at home. Of note, there were minor bruises over her lower legs and upper arms that were non-tender noted on her ER assessment on 02/17/22. No additional documentation of falls was noted in her EMR. Approximate onset date of 02/17/22 and cease date of 03/14/22 (date of participantâ€™s death from metastatic colon cancer).

RD 06/24/2022: There was concern on CT head/brain for ventriculomegaly and NPH; however, the resident had been informed that enlarged ventricles has been present as part of the ongoing Alzheimer's disease and that the diagnosis of NPH was inappropriate. MRI brain on 06/22/2022 showed chronic microvascular ischemic changes and hydrocephalus was unlikely to be due to NPH.  Pt. was seen by Dr George Gonzalez, neurologist, and he agreed that this was not NPH.  UA was clear, C & S is awaited. He did receive a dose of Rocephin.  EEG testing was recommended 06/23/2022, and showed probably normal EEG for patient who was drowsy throughout major portions of the recording. No further neurological work-up was required inpatient. From neurology standpoint, pt. has been discharged. 06/23/2022 the spouse reported that he was walking well, fully oriented and not confused. Pt. was diagnosed with a transient ischemic attack.  He is presently still in the hospital with plans for discharge later today, 06/24/2022.  Pt. will be following up with our clinic on an outpatient basis. Pt. has a history of TIA in 03/2014; atrial fibrillation onset 04/2012; myocardial infarction 10/2017; left heart catheterization with stent placement 10/2019; right carotid endarterectomy 04/2014; coronary artery disease 2012. 7/5/2022 MTG: Upon review of his hospital chart it was noted that the patient was discharged on 06/23/2022 from the hospital.

placement on mechanical ventilation. They all expressed that patient wishes as well as theirs, would be not to go on the breathing machine, i.e. no intubation or mechanical ventilation however, they would like to continue rest of medical management including antibiotics, and rest of medical management -I explained to them that additional antimicrobial will be a form of empiric therapy as it is difficult to determine exact pathogen to target given the inability to perform bronchoscopy and BAL, they
expressed full understanding to our discussion -Geriatric team as well as palliative care team will continue to follow-up with the patient -We have discussed with infectious disease team to continue current antimicrobial consider adding Bactrim for empiric treatment of PCP, given inability to perform diagnostic bronchoscopy with BAL due to risk of intubation given worsening respiratory status for the patient. -CLL status post chemotherapy
